# Security Review and Improvements for app.js

## Summary of Changes

This document outlines the security enhancements and best practices applied to the Express.js application.

---

## 1. Security Headers (helmet.js)

**What was added:**
```javascript
app.use(helmet());
```

**Why it matters:**
- Automatically sets HTTP security headers
- Protects against XSS, MIME type sniffing, clickjacking, etc.
- Industry standard for Express applications

**Benefits:**
- Defense against common web vulnerabilities
- Minimal performance overhead

---

## 2. CORS Configuration

**What was added:**
```javascript
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  res.header('Access-Control-Allow-Origin', process.env.ALLOWED_ORIGINS || 'localhost');
  res.header('Access-Control-Allow-Methods', 'GET, OPTIONS');
  res.header('Access-Control-Allow-Headers', 'Content-Type');
  next();
});
```

**Why it matters:**
- Restricts cross-origin requests
- Configurable via environment variables
- Only allows necessary HTTP methods

---

## 3. Rate Limiting

**What was added:**
```javascript
const limiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 minutes
  max: 100, // Limit each IP to 100 requests per windowMs
  ...
});
```

**Why it matters:**
- Protects against DOS and brute force attacks
- Prevents resource exhaustion
- Configurable thresholds

---

## 4. Request Body Size Limits

**What was added:**
```javascript
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ limit: '10kb', extended: false }));
```

**Why it matters:**
- Prevents large payload attacks
- Protects against memory exhaustion
- Avoids accidental file uploads

---

## 5. Input Validation & Sanitization

**What was added to `/users` endpoint:**
```javascript
// Validate allowed query parameters
const allowedQueryParams = new Set(['limit', 'offset']);
const invalidParams = Object.keys(req.query).filter(
  param => !allowedQueryParams.has(param)
);

// Sanitize and validate numeric inputs
const limit = Math.min(parseInt(req.query.limit, 10) || 10, 100);
const offset = Math.max(parseInt(req.query.offset, 10) || 0, 0);

// Type checking
if (isNaN(limit) || isNaN(offset)) {
  return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Invalid input', ... });
}
```

**Why it matters:**
- Prevents injection attacks
- Catches malformed requests early
- Protects against unexpected parameter abuse

---

## 6. Comprehensive Error Handling

**What was added:**

**Try-catch blocks:**
```javascript
app.get('/health', (req, res) => {
  try {
    res.json({ status: 'ok', timestamp: new Date().toISOString() });
  } catch (error) {
    handleError(res, error, 500);
  }
});
```

**Global error handler:**
```javascript
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  handleError(res, err, err.status || 500);
});

function handleError(res, error, statusCode = 500) {
  // Log error details
  console.error(`[${new Date().toISOString()}] Error:`, error.message);

  // Don't expose sensitive info in production
  const isDevelopment = process.env.NODE_ENV === 'development';
  res.status(statusCode).json({
    error: 'Internal Server Error',
    message: isDevelopment ? error.message : 'An unexpected error occurred',
    ...(isDevelopment && { stack: error.stack }),
  });
}
```

**Why it matters:**
- Prevents unhandled exceptions from crashing the server
- Controls information disclosure
- Enables proper logging and monitoring
- Different error responses for development vs production

---

## 7. Configuration via Environment Variables

**What was changed:**
```javascript
const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;
const server = app.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`);
});
```

**Why it matters:**
- Enables deployment flexibility
- Keeps secrets out of code
- Supports different environments

---

## 8. Graceful Shutdown

